[src:minitest/regression-testing] Changes that may require regression testing include bug fixes, software enhancements, configuration changes, and even substitution of electronic components (hardware).
[src:minitest/regression-testing] As regression test suites tend to grow with each found defect, test automation is frequently involved.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Sometimes a change impact analysis is performed to determine an appropriate subset of tests (*non-regression analysis*).
[src:minitest/regression-testing] As software is updated or changed, or reused on a modified target, emergence of new faults and/or re-emergence of old faults is quite common.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Sometimes re-emergence occurs because a fix gets lost through poor revision control practices (or simple human error in revision control).
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Often, a fix for a problem will be "fragile" in that it fixes the problem in the narrow case where it was first observed but not in more general cases which may arise over the lifetime of the software.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Frequently, a fix for a problem in one area inadvertently causes a software bug in another area.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] It may happen that when a feature is redesigned some of the same mistakes that were made in the original implementation of the feature also occur in the redesign.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] In most software development situations, it is considered good coding practice, when a bug is located and fixed, to record a test that exposes the bug and re-run that test regularly after subsequent changes to the program.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Although this may be done through manual testing procedures using programming techniques, it is often done using automated testing tools.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Common strategies are to run such a system after every successful compile (for small projects), every night, or once a week.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Those strategies can be automated by an external tool.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Regression testing is an integral part of the extreme programming software development method.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] In this method, design documents are replaced by extensive, repeatable, and automated testing of the entire software package throughout each stage of the software development process.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Regression testing is done after functional testing has concluded, to verify that the other functionalities are working.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] In the corporate world, regression testing has traditionally been performed by a software quality assurance team after the development team has completed work.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] However, defects found at this stage are the most costly to fix.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] This problem is being addressed by the rise of unit testing.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Although developers have always written test cases as part of the development cycle, these test cases have generally been either functional tests or unit tests that verify only intended outcomes.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Developer testing compels a developer to focus on unit testing and to include both positive and negative test cases.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] This technique checks all the test cases on the current program to check its integrity.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Though it is expensive as it needs to re-run all the test cases, it ensures that there are no errors because of the modified code.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Unlike Retest all, this technique runs a part of the test suite (owing to the cost of retest all) if the cost of selecting the part of the test suite is less than the Retest all technique.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Prioritize the test cases so as to increase a test suite's rate of fault detection.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Test case prioritization techniques schedule test cases so that the test cases that are higher in priority are executed before the test cases that have a lower priority.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] This technique is a hybrid of regression test selection and test case prioritization.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Regression testing is performed when changes are made to the existing functionality of the software or if there is a bug fix in the software.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Regression testing can be achieved through multiple approaches; if a *test all* approach is followed, it provides certainty that the changes made to the software have not affected the existing functionalities, which are unaltered.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] In agile software development—where the software development life cycles are very short, resources are scarce, and changes to the software are very frequent—regression testing might introduce a lot of unnecessary overhead.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Regression testing can be used not only for testing the *correctness* of a program but often also for tracking the quality of its output.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] For instance, in the design of a compiler, regression testing could track the code size and the time it takes to compile and execute the test suite cases.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] — Fred Brooks, *The Mythical Man Month*, p.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Regression tests can be done at any level, from unit through to system integration.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Functional tests exercise the complete program with various inputs.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] These tests are often automated due to the need for repetition, and may be done by test tools that are not part of the compiler suite.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Non-functional tests assess aspects such as performance, security, or reliability.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] Conducting non-functional regression tests presents additional challenges.
[src:minitest/regression-testing] For example, detecting changes in performance is often statistically complex, while security issues typically arise from vulnerabilities in the software ecosystem rather than from individual code changes.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is interpreted, high-level, and dynamically typed; its interpreter uses garbage collection and just-in-time compilation.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] It supports multiple programming paradigms, including procedural, object-oriented, and functional programming.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] According to the creator, Ruby was influenced by Perl, Smalltalk, Eiffel, Ada, BASIC, and Lisp.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] According to Matsumoto, Ruby was conceived in 1993.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto described Ruby's design as resembling a simple Lisp language at its core, with an object system like that of Smalltalk, blocks inspired by higher-order functions, and practical utility like that of Perl.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] The name "Ruby" originated during an online chat session between Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka on 24 February 1993, before any code had been written.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Two names were initially proposed: "Coral" and "Ruby".
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto chose the latter in a subsequent email to Ishitsuka.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] He also noted that one factor influencing the choice of the name was that a colleague's birthstone was ruby.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] The first public release of Ruby 0.95 was announced on Japanese domestic newsgroups on 21 December 1995.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Subsequently, three more versions of Ruby were released in two days.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] The release coincided with the launch of the Japanese-language *ruby-list* mailing list, which was the first mailing list for the new language.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Already present at this stage of development were many of the features familiar in later releases of Ruby, including object-oriented design, classes with inheritance, mixins, iterators, closures, exception handling and garbage collection.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] After the release of Ruby 0.95 in 1995, several stable versions of Ruby were released in these years.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] In 1997, the first article about Ruby was published on the Web.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] In the same year, Matsumoto was hired by netlab.jp to work on Ruby as a full-time developer.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] In 1998, the Ruby Application Archive was launched by Matsumoto, along with a simple English-language homepage for Ruby.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] In 1999, the first English language mailing list *ruby-talk* began, which signaled a growing interest in the language outside Japan.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] In this same year, Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka wrote the first book on Ruby, *The Object-oriented Scripting Language Ruby* (オブジェクト指向スクリプト言語 Ruby), which was published in Japan in October 1999.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] It would be followed in the early 2000s by around 20 books on Ruby published in Japanese.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] By 2000, Ruby was more popular than Python in Japan.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] In September 2000, the first English language book *Programming Ruby* was printed, which was later freely released to the public, further widening the adoption of Ruby amongst English speakers.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] In early 2002, the English-language *ruby-talk* mailing list was receiving more messages than the Japanese-language *ruby-list*, demonstrating Ruby's increasing popularity in the non-Japanese speaking world.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 was initially released in August 2003, was stable for a long time, and was retired in June 2013.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Although deprecated, there is still code based on it.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 is only partially compatible with Ruby 1.9.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 has been the subject of several industry standards.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] It was accepted as a Japanese Industrial Standard (JIS X 3017) in 2011 and an international standard (ISO/IEC 30170) in 2012.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Around 2005, interest in the Ruby language surged in tandem with Ruby on Rails, a web framework written in Ruby.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Rails is frequently credited with increasing awareness of Ruby.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Effective with Ruby 1.9.3, released 31 October 2011, Ruby switched from being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the GPL to being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the two-clause BSD license.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Adoption of 1.9 was slowed by changes from 1.8 that required many popular third party gems to be rewritten.
