[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] As of the official 2.0.0 release on 24 February 2013, there were only five known incompatibilities.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Starting with 2.1.0, Ruby's versioning policy changed to be more similar to semantic versioning, although it differs slightly in that minor version increments may be API incompatible.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.2.0 includes speed-ups, bugfixes, and library updates and removes some deprecated APIs.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Most notably, Ruby 2.2.0 introduces changes to memory handling – an incremental garbage collector, support for garbage collection of symbols and the option to compile directly against jemalloc.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] It also contains experimental support for using vfork(2) with system() and spawn(), and added support for the Unicode 7.0 specification.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Since version 2.2.1, Ruby MRI performance on PowerPC64 was improved.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Features that were made obsolete or removed include callcc, the DL library, Digest::HMAC, lib/rational.rb, lib/complex.rb, GServer, Logger::Application as well as various C API functions.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.3.0 includes many performance improvements, updates, and bugfixes including changes to Proc#call, Socket and IO use of exception keywords, Thread#name handling, default passive Net::FTP connections, and Rake being removed from stdlib.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.4.0 includes performance improvements to hash table, Array#max, Array#min, and instance variable access.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.6.0 include an experimental just-in-time compiler (JIT), and *RubyVM::AbstractSyntaxTree* (experimental).
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.7.0 include pattern Matching (experimental), REPL improvements, a compaction GC, and separation of positional and keyword arguments.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0.0 was released on Christmas Day in 2020.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] It is known as Ruby 3x3, which signifies that programs would run three times faster in Ruby 3.0 comparing to Ruby 2.0. and some had already been implemented in intermediate releases on the road from 2 to 3.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] To achieve 3x3, Ruby 3 comes with MJIT, and later YJIT, Just-In-Time Compilers, to make programs faster, although they are described as experimental and remain disabled by default (enabled by flags at runtime).
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Another goal of Ruby 3.0 is to improve concurrency and two more utilities Fibre Scheduler, and experimental Ractor facilitate the goal.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ractor is light-weight and thread-safe as it is achieved by exchanging messages rather than shared objects.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0 introduces RBS language to describe the types of Ruby programs for static analysis.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] It is separated from general Ruby programs.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and library changes in Ruby 3.0 as well.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.1 was released on 25 December 2021.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] It includes YJIT, a new, experimental, Just-In-Time Compiler developed by Shopify, to enhance the performance of real world business applications.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and other improvements in this release.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Network libraries for FTP, SMTP, IMAP, and POP are moved from default gems to bundled gems.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.2 was released on 25 December 2022.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] It brings support for being run inside of a WebAssembly environment via a WASI interface.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Regular expressions also receives some improvements, including a faster, memoized matching algorithm to protect against certain ReDoS attacks, and configurable timeouts for regular expression matching.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Additional debugging and syntax features are also included in this release, which include syntax suggestion, as well as error highlighting.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] The MJIT compiler has been re-implemented as a standard library module, while the YJIT, a Rust-based JIT compiler now supports more architectures on Linux.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 was released on 25 December 2023.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 introduces significant enhancements and performance improvements to the language.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Key features include the introduction of the Prism parser for portable and maintainable parsing, the addition of the pure-Ruby JIT compiler RJIT, and major performance boosts in the YJIT compiler.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Additionally, improvements in memory usage, the introduction of an M:N thread scheduler, and updates to the standard library contribute to a more efficient and developer-friendly Ruby ecosystem.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 was released on 25 December 2024.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 adds `it` block parameter reference, changes Prism as default parser, adds Happy Eyeballs Version 2 support to socket library, improves YJIT, adds modular Garbage Collector and so on.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] It adds experimental ZJIT, a JIT written in Rust, and experimental "Ruby Box", a feature to provide separation about definitions.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] It was decided to bump the version number to 4.0 instead of 3.5 to celebrate Rubys 30. birthday.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto stated that Ruby is designed for programmer productivity and fun, following the principles of good user interface design.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] At a Google Tech Talk in 2008 he said, "I hope to see Ruby help every programmer in the world to be productive, and to enjoy programming, and to be happy.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto has said his primary design goal was to make a language that he himself enjoyed using, by minimizing programmer work and possible confusion.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] If that personal standard remains consistent, there would be few surprises for those familiar with the standard.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is object-oriented: every value is an object, including classes and instances of types that many other languages designate as primitives (such as integers, Booleans, and "null").
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Because everything in Ruby is an object, everything in Ruby has certain built-in abilities called methods.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Every function is a method and methods are always called on an object.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Methods defined at the top level scope become methods of the Object class.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Since this class is an ancestor of every other class, such methods can be called on any object.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] They are also visible in all scopes, effectively serving as "global" procedures.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby supports inheritance with dynamic dispatch, mixins and singleton methods (belonging to, and defined for, a single instance rather than being defined on the class).
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Though Ruby does not support multiple inheritance, classes can import modules as mixins.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] It has support for introspection, reflective programming, metaprogramming, and interpreter-based threads.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby features dynamic typing, and supports parametric polymorphism.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] According to the Ruby FAQ, the syntax is similar to Perl's and the semantics are similar to Smalltalk's, but the design philosophy differs greatly from Python's.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] The syntax of Ruby is broadly similar to that of Perl and Python.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Class and method definitions are signaled by keywords, whereas code blocks can be defined by either keywords or braces.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] In contrast to Perl, variables are not obligatorily prefixed with a sigil.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] When used, the sigil changes the semantics of scope of the variable.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] For practical purposes there is no distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Line breaks are significant and taken as the end of a statement; a semicolon may be equivalently used.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Unlike Python, indentation is not significant.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] One of the differences from Python and Perl is that Ruby keeps all of its instance variables completely private to the class and only exposes them through accessor methods (`attr_writer`, `attr_reader`, etc.).
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Unlike the "getter" and "setter" methods of other languages like C++ or Java, accessor methods in Ruby can be created with a single line of code via metaprogramming; however, accessor methods can also be created in the traditional fashion of C++ and Java.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] As invocation of these methods does not require the use of parentheses, it is trivial to change an instance variable into a full function, without modifying a single line of calling code or having to do any refactoring achieving similar functionality to C# and VB.NET property members.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Python's property descriptors are similar, but come with a trade-off in the development process.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] If one begins in Python by using a publicly exposed instance variable, and later changes the implementation to use a private instance variable exposed through a property descriptor, code internal to the class may need to be adjusted to use the private variable rather than the public property.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby's design forces all instance variables to be private, but also provides a simple way to declare `set` and `get` methods.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] This is in keeping with the idea that in Ruby, one never directly accesses the internal members of a class from outside the class; rather, one passes a message to the class and receives a response.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] The original Ruby interpreter is often referred to as Matz's Ruby Interpreter or MRI.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] This implementation is written in C and uses its own Ruby-specific virtual machine.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] The standardized and retired Ruby 1.8 implementation was written in C, as a single-pass interpreted language.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Starting with Ruby 1.9, and continuing with Ruby 2.x and above, the official Ruby interpreter has been YARV ("Yet Another Ruby VM"), and this implementation has superseded the slower virtual machine used in previous releases of MRI.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] As of 2026, there are a number of alternative implementations of Ruby, including JRuby, Rubinius, and mruby.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Each takes a different approach, with JRuby and Rubinius providing just-in-time compilation and mruby also providing ahead-of-time compilation.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] The maturity of Ruby implementations tends to be measured by their ability to run the Ruby on Rails (Rails) framework, because it is complex to implement and uses many Ruby-specific features.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] The point when a particular implementation achieves this goal is called "the Rails singularity".
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] The reference implementation, JRuby, and Rubinius are all able to run Rails unmodified in a production environment.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto originally developed Ruby on the 4.3BSD-based Sony NEWS-OS 3.x, but later migrated his work to SunOS 4.x, and finally to Linux.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] By 1999, Ruby was known to work across many different operating systems.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Modern Ruby versions and implementations are available on all major desktop, mobile and server-based operating systems.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is also supported across a number of cloud hosting platforms like Jelastic, Heroku, Google Cloud Platform and others.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Tools such as RVM and RBEnv, facilitate installation and partitioning of multiple ruby versions, and multiple 'gemsets' on one machine.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] A Ruby package is called a "gem" and can be installed via the command line.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Most gems are libraries, though a few exist that are applications, such as IDEs.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] There are over 100,000 Ruby gems hosted on RubyGems.org.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] Many new and existing Ruby libraries are hosted on GitHub, a service that offers version control repository hosting for Git.
[src:minitest/ruby-programming-language] The Ruby Application Archive, which hosted applications, documentation, and libraries for Ruby programming, was maintained until 2013, when its function was transferred to RubyGems.
[src:minitest/test-automation] Automation provides many benefits over manual testing.
[src:minitest/test-automation] For API testing, tests drive the SUT via its application programming interface (API).
[src:minitest/test-automation] Compared to manual testing, automated API testing often can execute a relatively large number of cases in a relatively short time.
[src:minitest/test-automation] For GUI testing, tests drive the SUT via its graphical user interface (GUI) by generating events such as keystrokes and mouse clicks.
[src:minitest/test-automation] Automated GUI testing can be challenging to develop, but can run much faster than a human could perform the same testing.
[src:minitest/test-automation] When automated testing is in place, regression testing can be a relatively quick and easy operation.
[src:minitest/test-automation] Instead of a significant outlay of human time and effort, a regression test run could require nothing more than a push of a button and even starting the run can be automated.
[src:minitest/test-automation] The following are notable testing techniques categorized as test automation.
[src:minitest/test-automation] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to assess the business risk of releasing the SUT.
[src:minitest/test-automation] The scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:minitest/test-automation] For model-based testing, the SUT is modeled and test cases can be generated from it to support no code test development.
[src:minitest/test-automation] Some tools support the encoding of test cases as plain English that can be used on multiple operating systems, browsers, and smart devices.
[src:minitest/test-automation] Test-driven development (TDD) inherently includes the generation of automation test code.
[src:minitest/test-automation] Unit test code is written while the SUT code is written.
[src:minitest/test-automation] When the code is complete, the tests are complete as well.
[src:minitest/test-automation] A review of 52 practitioner and 26 academic sources found that five main factors to consider in test automation decision are: system under test (SUT), scope of testing, test toolset, human and organizational topics, cross-cutting factors.
[src:minitest/test-automation] The factors most frequently identified were: need for regression testing, economic factors, and maturity of SUT.
[src:minitest/test-automation] While the reusability of automated tests is valued by software development companies, this property can also be viewed as a disadvantage as it leads to a plateau effect, where repeatedly executing the same tests stops detecting errors.
[src:minitest/test-automation] Testing tools can help automate tasks such as product installation, test data creation, GUI interaction, problem detection (consider parsing or polling agents equipped with test oracles), defect logging, etc., without necessarily automating tests in an end-to-end fashion.
[src:minitest/test-automation] To support coded automated testing, the test engineer or software quality assurance person must have software coding ability.
[src:minitest/test-automation] Some testing techniques such as table-driven and no-code can lessen or alleviate the need for programming skill.
[src:minitest/test-automation] A test automation framework provides a programming environment that integrates test logic, test data, and other resources.
[src:minitest/test-automation] The framework provides the basis of test automation and simplifies the automation effort.
[src:minitest/test-automation] Using a framework can lower the cost of test development and maintenance.
[src:minitest/test-automation] If there is change to any test case then only the test case file needs to be updated and the driver script and startup script will remain the same.
[src:minitest/test-automation] A framework is responsible for defining the format in which to express expectations, providing a mechanism to hook into or drive the SUT, executing the tests, and reporting results.
[src:minitest/test-automation] A test automation interface is a platform that provides a workspace for incorporating multiple testing tools and frameworks for system/integration testing.
[src:minitest/test-automation] A test automation interface may simplify the process of mapping tests to business criteria without coding.
[src:minitest/test-automation] A test automation interface may improve the efficiency and flexibility of maintaining tests.
[src:minitest/test-automation] The parser is present to parse the object files coming from the object repository into the test specific scripting language.
[src:minitest/test-automation] Collection of UI/Application object data recorded by the testing tool while exploring the SUT.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] A **test fixture** is a device used to consistently test some item, device, or piece of software.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Test fixtures are used in the testing of electronics, software and physical devices.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] In testing electronic equipment such as circuit boards, electronic components, and chips, a test fixture is a device or setup designed to hold the device under test in place and allow it to be tested by being subjected to controlled electronic test signals.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Examples are a bed of nails tester or smart fixture.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Test fixtures can come in different shapes, sizes, and functions.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] There are several different types of test fixtures, including In-Circuit Test Fixtures, Functional Test Fixtures, and Wireless Test Fixtures.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] In Circuit Test (ICT) fixtures individually test each component on a PCB, while functional test fixtures assess the entire board's functionality.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Functional test fixtures simulate real-world conditions, whereas ICT is more focused on detecting assembly defects like short circuits or missing components.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] An In-Circuit Test fixture can come in both Inline and Standard variations.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] An Inline Test Fixture is designed for fast, automated testing directly within a production line, ideal for high-volume manufacturing where continuous testing maximises efficiency.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] A Standard Test Fixture, on the other hand, usually requires manual loading, making it well-suited to smaller-scale or specialised testing.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] In the context of software, a test fixture (also called "test context") is used to set up the system state and input data needed for test execution.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] For example, the Ruby on Rails web framework uses YAML to initialize a database with known parameters before running a test.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] This allows for tests to be repeatable, which is one of the key features of an effective test framework.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] In most cases, a custom test fixture will normally require custom test software.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] This software is created in order to ensure optimal testing performance and seamless integration.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] The custom software can be configured to carry out a number of different tests from BIST (Built-In Self Test) to advanced JTAG Implementation.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Test fixtures can be set up three different ways: in-line, delegate, and implicit.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Delegate setup places the test fixture in a separate standalone helper method that is accessed by multiple test methods.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Implicit setup places the test fixture in a setup method which is used to set up multiple test methods.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] This differs from delegate setup in that the overall setup of multiple tests is in a single setup method where the test fixture gets created rather than each test method having its own setup procedures and linking to an external test fixture.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] The main advantage of a test fixture is that it allows for tests to be repeatable since each test is always starting with the same setup.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Test fixtures also ease test code design by allowing the developer to separate methods into different functions and reuse each function for other tests.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Further, test fixtures preconfigure tests into a known initial state instead of working with whatever was left from a previous test run.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] A disadvantage is that it could lead to duplication of test fixtures if using in-line setup.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] It is considered bad practice when implicit test fixtures are too general, or when a test method sets up a test fixture and does not use it during the test.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] A more subtle issue is if the test methods ignore certain fields within the test fixture.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Another bad practice is a test setup that contains more steps than needed for the test; this is a problem seen in in-line setup.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] A test case is considered "unsafe" when it modifies its fixture(s).
[src:minitest/test-fixture] An unsafe test case can render subsequent tests useless by leaving the fixture in an unexpected state.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] It also causes the order of tests to be important: a modified fixture must be reset if more tests are to be run after an unsafe test.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Examples of fixtures include loading a database with a specific known set of data, erasing a hard disk and installing a known clean operating system installation, copying a specific known set of files, or the preparation of input data as well as set-up and creation of mock objects.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Software which is used to run reproducible tests systematically on a piece of software under test is known as a test harness; part of its job is to set up suitable test fixtures.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] In generic xUnit, a *test fixture* is all the things that must be in place in order to run a test and expect a particular outcome.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Frequently fixtures are created by handling *setUp()* and *tearDown()* events of the unit testing framework.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] In *setUp()* one would create the expected state for the test and in *tearDown()* it would clean up what had been set up.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] In physical testing, a fixture is a device or apparatus to hold or support the test specimen during the test.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] The influence of test fixtures on test results is important and is an ongoing subject of research.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Many test methods detail the requirements of test fixtures in the text of the document.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Some fixtures employ clamps, wedge grips and pincer grips.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Further types of construction include eccentric roller fixtures, thread grips and button head grips and rope grips.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Mechanical holding apparatuses provide the clamping force via arms, wedges or eccentric wheel to the jaws.
[src:minitest/test-fixture] Additionally there are pneumatic and hydraulic fixtures for tensile testing that allow very fast clamping procedures and very high clamping forces.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing describes tests that are run at the unit-level to contrast testing at the integration or system level.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing, as a principle for testing separately smaller parts of large software systems, dates back to the early days of software engineering.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In June 1956 at US Navy's Symposium on Advanced Programming Methods for Digital Computers, H.D.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] It featured a specification-based approach where the coding phase was followed by "parameter testing" to validate component subprograms against their specification, followed then by an "assembly testing" for parts put together.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In 1964, a similar approach is described for the software of the Mercury project, where individual units developed by different programmers underwent "unit tests" before being integrated together.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In 1969, testing methodologies appear more structured, with unit tests, component tests and integration tests collectively validating individual parts written separately and their progressive assembly into larger blocks.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Some public standards adopted in the late 1960s, such as MIL-STD-483 and MIL-STD-490, contributed further to a wide acceptance of unit testing in large projects.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing was in those times interactive or automated, using either coded tests or capture and replay testing tools.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In 1989, Kent Beck described a testing framework for Smalltalk (later called SUnit) in "Simple Smalltalk Testing: With Patterns".
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In 1997, Kent Beck and Erich Gamma developed and released JUnit, a unit test framework that became popular with Java developers.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Google embraced automated testing around 2005–2006.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] A unit is defined as a single behaviour exhibited by the system under test (SUT), usually corresponding to a requirement.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] While a unit may correspond to a single function or module (in procedural programming) or a single method or class (in object-oriented programming), functions/methods and modules/classes do not necessarily correspond to units.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] From the system requirements perspective only the perimeter of the system is relevant, thus only entry points to externally visible system behaviours define units.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit tests can be performed manually or via automated test execution.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Automated tests include benefits such as: running tests often, running tests without staffing cost, and consistent and repeatable testing.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Testing is often performed by the programmer who writes and modifies the code under test.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing may be viewed as part of the process of writing code.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] During development, a programmer may code criteria, or results that are known to be good, into the test to verify the unit's correctness.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] During test execution, frameworks log tests that fail any criterion and report them in a summary.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] For this, the most commonly used approach is test - function - expected value.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Test cases underlie testing that is methodical rather than haphazard.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] A battery of test cases can be built to produce the desired coverage of the software being tested.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Formally defined test cases allow the same tests to be run repeatedly against successive versions of the software, allowing for effective and consistent regression testing.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] A test double is software used in software test automation that satisfies a dependency so that the test need not depend on production code.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] A test double provides functionality via an interface that the software under test cannot distinguish from production code.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] A parameterized test is a test that accepts a set of values that can be used to enable the test to run with multiple, different input values.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] A testing framework that supports parametrized tests supports a way to encode parameter sets and to run the test with each set.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Use of parametrized tests can reduce test code duplication.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Parameterized tests are supported by TestNG, JUnit, XUnit and NUnit, as well as in various JavaScript test frameworks.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Parameters for the unit tests may be coded manually or in some cases are automatically generated by the test framework.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In recent years support was added for writing more powerful (unit) tests, leveraging the concept of theories, test cases that execute the same steps, but using test data generated at runtime, unlike regular parameterized tests that use the same execution steps with input sets that are pre-defined.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Test code needs access to the code it is testing, but testing should not compromise normal design goals such as information hiding, encapsulation and the separation of concerns.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] To enable access to code not exposed in the external API, unit tests can be located in the same project or module as the code being tested.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In object oriented design this still may not provide access to private data and methods.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Therefore, extra work may be necessary for unit tests.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In Java and other languages, a developer can use reflection to access private fields and methods.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Alternatively, an inner class can be used to hold the unit tests so they have visibility of the enclosing class's members and attributes.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In the .NET Framework and some other programming languages, partial classes may be used to expose private methods and data for the tests to access.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] It is important that code solely for accommodating tests does not remain in the production code.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In C and other languages, compiler directives such as `#if DEBUG ... #endif` can be placed around such additional classes and indeed all other test-related code to prevent them being compiled into the released code.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] This means the released code is not exactly the same as what was unit tested.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] The regular running of fewer but more comprehensive, end-to-end, integration tests on the final release build can ensure (among other things) that no production code exists that subtly relies on aspects of the test harness.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] There is some debate among developers, as to whether it is wise to test private methods and data anyway.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Some argue that private members are a mere implementation detail that may change, and should be allowed to do so without breaking numbers of tests.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Thus it should be sufficient to test any class through its public interface or through its subclass interface, which some languages call the "protected" interface.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Others say that crucial aspects of functionality may be implemented in private methods and testing them directly offers advantage of smaller and more direct unit tests.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In test-driven development (TDD), unit tests are written before the related production code is written.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Starting with a failing test, then adds *just enough* production code to make the test pass, then refactors the code as makes sense and then repeats by adding another failing test.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing is intended to ensure that the units meet their design and behave as intended.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] By writing tests first for the smallest testable units, then the compound behaviors between those, one can build up comprehensive tests for complex applications.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] One goal of unit testing is to isolate each part of the program and show that the individual parts are correct.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] A unit test provides a strict, written contract that the piece of code must satisfy.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing finds problems early in the development cycle.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] This includes both bugs in the programmer's implementation and flaws or missing parts of the specification for the unit.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] The process of writing a thorough set of tests forces the author to think through inputs, outputs, and error conditions, and thus more crisply define the unit's desired behavior.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] The cost of finding a bug before coding begins or when the code is first written is considerably lower than the cost of detecting, identifying, and correcting the bug later.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Bugs in released code may also cause costly problems for the end-users of the software.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Code can be impossible or difficult to unit test if poorly written, thus unit testing can force developers to structure functions and objects in better ways.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing enables more frequent releases in software development.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] By testing individual components in isolation, developers can quickly identify and address issues, leading to faster iteration and release cycles.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing allows the programmer to refactor code or upgrade system libraries at a later date, and make sure the module still works correctly (e.g., in regression testing).
[src:minitest/unit-testing] The procedure is to write test cases for all functions and methods so that whenever a change causes a fault, it can be identified quickly.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit tests detect changes which may break a design contract.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing may reduce uncertainty in the units themselves and can be used in a bottom-up testing style approach.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] By testing the parts of a program first and then testing the sum of its parts, integration testing becomes much easier.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Some programmers contend that unit tests provide a form of documentation of the code.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Developers wanting to learn what functionality is provided by a unit, and how to use it, can review the unit tests to gain an understanding of it.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Test cases can embody characteristics that are critical to the success of the unit.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] These characteristics can indicate appropriate/inappropriate use of a unit as well as negative behaviors that are to be trapped by the unit.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] A test case documents these critical characteristics, although many software development environments do not rely solely upon code to document the product in development.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In some processes, the act of writing tests and the code under test, plus associated refactoring, may take the place of formal design.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Each unit test can be seen as a design element specifying classes, methods, and observable behavior.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Testing will not catch every error in the program, because it cannot evaluate every execution path in any but the most trivial programs.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] This problem is a superset of the halting problem, which is undecidable.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Additionally, unit testing by definition only tests the functionality of the units themselves.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Therefore, it will not catch integration errors or broader system-level errors (such as functions performed across multiple units, or non-functional test areas such as performance).
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing should be done in conjunction with other software testing activities, as they can only show the presence or absence of particular errors; they cannot prove a complete absence of errors.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] To guarantee correct behavior for every execution path and every possible input, and ensure the absence of errors, other techniques are required, namely the application of formal methods to prove that a software component has no unexpected behavior.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] An elaborate hierarchy of unit tests does not equal integration testing.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Integration with peripheral units should be included in integration tests, but not in unit tests.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Integration testing typically still relies heavily on humans testing manually; high-level or global-scope testing can be difficult to automate, such that manual testing often appears faster and cheaper.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Software testing is a combinatorial problem.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] For example, every Boolean decision statement requires at least two tests: one with an outcome of "true" and one with an outcome of "false".
[src:minitest/unit-testing] As a result, for every line of code written, programmers often need 3 to 5 lines of test code.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] This obviously takes time and its investment may not be worth the effort.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] There are problems that cannot easily be tested at all – for example those that are nondeterministic or involve multiple threads.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In addition, code for a unit test is as likely to be buggy as the code it is testing.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Another challenge related to writing the unit tests is the difficulty of setting up realistic and useful tests.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] It is necessary to create relevant initial conditions so the part of the application being tested behaves like part of the complete system.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] If these initial conditions are not set correctly, the test will not be exercising the code in a realistic context, which diminishes the value and accuracy of unit test results.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] To obtain the intended benefits from unit testing, rigorous discipline is needed throughout the software development process.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] It is essential to keep careful records not only of the tests that have been performed, but also of all changes that have been made to the source code of this or any other unit in the software.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Use of a version control system is essential.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] If a later version of the unit fails a particular test that it had previously passed, the version-control software can provide a list of the source code changes (if any) that have been applied to the unit since that time.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] It is also essential to implement a sustainable process for ensuring that test case failures are reviewed regularly and addressed immediately.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] If such a process is not implemented and ingrained into the team's workflow, the application will evolve out of sync with the unit test suite, increasing false positives and reducing the effectiveness of the test suite.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing embedded system software presents challenges because the software is being developed on a different platform than the one it will eventually run on, making it difficult to run a test program in the actual deployment environment, as is possible with desktop programs.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit tests tend to be easiest when a method has input parameters and some output.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] It is not as easy to create unit tests when a major function of the method is to interact with something external to the application.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] For example, a method that will work with a database might require a mock up of database interactions to be created, which probably won't be as comprehensive as the real database interactions.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Below is an example of a JUnit test suite.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] The test suite uses assert statements to verify the expected result of various input values to the `sum` method.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Using unit-tests as a design specification has one significant advantage over other design methods: The design document (the unit-tests themselves) can itself be used to verify the implementation.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] The tests will never pass unless the developer implements a solution according to the design.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing lacks some of the accessibility of a diagrammatic specification such as a UML diagram, but they may be generated from the unit test using automated tools.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Most modern languages have free tools (usually available as extensions to IDEs).
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Free tools, like those based on the xUnit framework, outsource to another system the graphical rendering of a view for human consumption.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing is the cornerstone of extreme programming, which relies on an automated unit testing framework.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] This automated unit testing framework can be either third party, e.g., xUnit, or created within the development group.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Extreme programming uses the creation of unit tests for test-driven development.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] The developer writes a unit test that exposes either a software requirement or a defect.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] This test will fail because either the requirement isn't implemented yet, or because it intentionally exposes a defect in the existing code.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Then, the developer writes the simplest code to make the test, along with other tests, pass.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Most code in a system is unit tested, but not necessarily all paths through the code.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Extreme programming mandates a "test everything that can possibly break" strategy, over the traditional "test every execution path" method.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] This leads developers to develop fewer tests than classical methods, but this isn't really a problem, more a restatement of fact, as classical methods have rarely ever been followed methodically enough for all execution paths to have been thoroughly tested.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Extreme programming simply recognizes that testing is rarely exhaustive (because it is often too expensive and time-consuming to be economically viable) and provides guidance on how to effectively focus limited resources.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Crucially, the test code is considered a first class project artifact in that it is maintained at the same quality as the implementation code, with all duplication removed.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Developers release unit testing code to the code repository in conjunction with the code it tests.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Extreme programming's thorough unit testing allows the benefits mentioned above, such as simpler and more confident code development and refactoring, simplified code integration, accurate documentation, and more modular designs.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] These unit tests are also constantly run as a form of regression test.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Unit testing is also critical to the concept of Emergent Design, which develops software design iteratively through short test-driven development cycles of writing a unit test, making it pass, and refactoring; unit tests provide the regression safety net that makes continuous refactoring safe.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] An automated testing framework provides features for automating test execution and can accelerate writing and running tests.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Frameworks have been developed for a wide variety of programming languages.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Generally, frameworks are third-party, not distributed with a compiler or integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Tests can be written without using a framework to exercise the code under test using assertions, exception handling, and other control flow mechanisms to verify behavior and report failure.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Some note that testing without a framework is valuable since there is a barrier to entry for the adoption of a framework, and that having some tests is better than none – but once a framework is in place, adding tests can be easier.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] In some frameworks advanced test features are missing and must be hand-coded.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Some programming languages directly support unit testing.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Their grammar allows the direct declaration of unit tests without importing a library (whether third party or standard).
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Additionally, the Boolean conditions of the unit tests can be expressed in the same syntax as Boolean expressions used in non-unit test code, such as what is used for `if` and `while` statements.
[src:minitest/unit-testing] Some languages do not have built-in unit-testing support but have established unit testing libraries or frameworks.
